Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Monday! I had a lot of fun writing this one.=20
While I=E2=80=99ve written about AI, I haven=E2=80=99t written much about O=
penAI because there=E2=80=99s already so much attention on the company that=
 it=E2=80=99s been hard to find much new to say. GPT-4 is amazing. There wi=
ll be implications for white collar workers. Here are 75 things you didn=E2=
=80=99t know you could do with ChatGPT =F0=9F=A7=B5 =F0=9F=91=87 Are founda=
tion models defensible? Are GPT Wrappers defensible?=20
Then, on Thursday, OpenAI introduced ChatGPT plugins, and the more I though=
t about it, the more excited I got. Through a series of seeming accidents, =
great product, and user pull, OpenAI has attracted attention, turned that a=
ttention into the must-use API, and with the release of plugins, is turning=
 that attention into a platform unlike any platform that exists, one that i=
ngests the capabilities of the apps built on it.
If OpenAI chooses to, it can build an Apex Aggregator and define the new be=
st business model on the internet. We need to lay some groundwork to explai=
n why.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=C2=A0
Attention is All You Need
The paper that kicked off the AI Revolution had a catchy title, as these pa=
pers go: Attention is All You Need [ https://substack.com/redirect/0cfd18c1=
-ec6b-4194-8d01-2e5e5348f3b3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXX=
epKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=C2=A0
Written by a team at Google Brain in 2017, the paper introduced the now-fam=
ous Transformer architecture that powers large language models such as Open=
AI=E2=80=99s GPT-4.=C2=A0
As Chroma [ https://substack.com/redirect/fdc1c1c1-76bc-4c47-b46c-960085b18=
b2e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] co=
-founder Anton Troynikov [ https://substack.com/redirect/d654c98d-2149-4b75=
-950d-687932066400?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ] explained it to me in our first episode of  [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/09eb288e-1208-411d-8ed8-6=
53b8a48405e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]Anton Teaches Packy AI [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/09eb288e-1208-411d-8ed8-653b8a48405e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Transformers can do=
 a lot just by paying attention to the right parts of the input. They don't=
 need other types of neural network layers, like the ones used for convolut=
ions or recurrent connections, to perform well. Attention is all they need.
That same year, in a follow-up to his canonical Aggregation Theory [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/2a3351dc-4719-493d-8f7d-490e45186d38?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Ben Thompson wrote =
Defining Aggregators [ https://substack.com/redirect/04f92e4d-0b1d-4584-a96=
1-4e7390f5444f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8E=
xkRNpU ], to catalog businesses that capture value by controlling demand fo=
r abundant resources. Aggregators have three defining characteristics:
Direct Relationships with Users
Zero Marginal Cost for Serving Users
Demand-driven Multi-sided Networks with Decreasing Acquisition Costs
Think Google and Facebook, the Super-Aggregators. Billions of users come to=
 their sites, where they=E2=80=99re served content created by other people =
for free, and it gets cheaper to acquire users over time as demand attracts=
 supply which attracts more demand which attracts more supply, and so on. B=
etter experience leads to more users which leads to more suppliers and adve=
rtisers which leads to more users, and so on.=C2=A0
The takeaway from that post was essentially the same as the Transformer pap=
er: to win big on the internet, attention is all you need.=C2=A0
OpenAI [ https://substack.com/redirect/f0cc00af-7374-4e22-b264-e2c9ee968aa2=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] began=
 its life in December 2015 as a non-profit. With over $1 billion committed =
by Elon Musk, Peter Thiel, Sam Altman, Jessica Livingston, Reid Hoffman, Il=
ya Sutskever, and others, it had no plans to make money. It didn=E2=80=99t =
need to support itself.=C2=A0
One prominent VC who looked at investing early on said he loved the idea an=
d the team, but that with no revenue and no plans to make any, he couldn=E2=
=80=99t justify investing his LPs=E2=80=99 money in the startup. As recentl=
y as last summer, when DALL=E2=80=A2E 2 brought OpenAI into the limelight, =
a team member told me that while their tech was excellent, they weren=E2=80=
=99t quite sure how they were going to monetize it.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Then, in December, OpenAI released ChatGPT. The team wasn=E2=80=99t expecti=
ng much [ https://substack.com/redirect/ef0f99d5-14fe-4db4-b4e0-ee3bd14beb4=
a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =E2=
=80=93 it was a =E2=80=9Cresearch preview=E2=80=9D =E2=80=93 but practicall=
y overnight, it caught fire. Its December release was one of those =E2=80=
=9CI remember where I was when=E2=80=9D moments for those of us who love th=
is stuff (I was in a hotel lobby in LA and tweeted this [ https://substack.=
com/redirect/30923267-df2e-4326-932c-129c1ff5f64a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb=
8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] after my first experience).=C2=
=A0
ChatGPT exploded. Two months in, it reached 100 million users. Nearly half =
of the YC W23 class is building apps using OpenAI=E2=80=99s APIs. GPT-4 bec=
ame the most eagerly anticipated drop since the last Beatles album, and it =
delivered. Then last week, OpenAI released ChatGPT plugins [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/8a25df10-e567-4922-a26f-84ee80c16d1e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ]. They downplayed their fores=
ight on this one too, explaining the launch by saying: =E2=80=9CUsers have =
been asking for plugins since we launched ChatGPT.=E2=80=9D
Since the launch on Thursday, a bunch of people have compared plugins to Ap=
ple=E2=80=99s App Store, which paid developers $60 billion in 2022 (and lik=
ely took $15 billion for itself). I think it has the potential to be much b=
igger than that, and I really don=E2=80=99t want to be yet another person w=
ho overhypes OpenAI, so I=E2=80=99ll spend this entire piece walking you th=
rough why I think so.=C2=A0
In under a year, OpenAI has gone from under-the-radar and unsure-how-to-mon=
etize to one of the most potentially dominant strategic positions and busin=
ess models in the history of tech. It happened almost by accident. While th=
e technology deserves the praise it receives, its translation into a jugger=
naut business was far from certain until tens of millions of people rushed =
to use its new consumer-friendly interface. Since then, the dominos have fa=
llen rapidly.=C2=A0
When it comes to turning mind-blowing technology into an equally mind-blowi=
ng business opportunity, it turns out, you guessed it: attention is all you=
 need.
As it stands today, if OpenAI chooses to, it can build the Apex Aggregator =
by building an Action Engine. The Action Engine subsumes search and any num=
ber of products that let users do things, and it does them for users with n=
othing more than a simple prompt. If Aggregators controlled demand and comm=
oditized supply, the Apex Aggregator can control demand on multiple fronts,=
 turn attention into actions, disaggregate any supplier that feeds it, and =
even aggregate the aggregators. It could make Apple, Google, and Facebook=
=E2=80=99s models seem soft and cuddly=E2=80=A6 until they fight back.
I=E2=80=99ll explain what=E2=80=99s gotten me so excited about OpenAI=E2=80=
=99s accidental business model, but first, we need to do a quick refresher =
on the current tech business model kings.=C2=A0
The Super-Aggregators
If you=E2=80=99re reading this, I assume you know a lot about how Google an=
d Facebook=E2=80=99s business models =E2=80=93 the greatest cash-generating=
 machines known to humanity =E2=80=93 work, so I=E2=80=99ll keep this secti=
on very brief.=C2=A0
Facebook (and its family of apps) use billions of users to attract billions=
 of users, collect a lot of data on those users, and let advertisers target=
 those users based on that data. If you=E2=80=99re a company that wants to =
get in front of a lot of a certain type of buyer because you think that typ=
e of buyer might like your product, Facebook is the place to go. Then, you =
just serve them a colorful ad, a certain number of them will click on it, a=
nd a certain number of those will buy. Because Facebook has the most social=
 attention =E2=80=93 over 3 billion users =E2=80=93 it attracts more people=
, and because it has the most people and the most data on them, it attracts=
 the most brand advertising dollars. Both demand and supply cost it practic=
ally nothing to acquire, and ads cost it practically nothing to serve.=C2=
=A0
Google=E2=80=99s model is even more direct. Billions of people go to Google=
 explicitly to tell the site exactly what they=E2=80=99re looking for =E2=
=80=93 from information to hotels in certain cities to accounting software =
=E2=80=93 and Google auctions off well-placed links to advertisers who offe=
r exactly what those people are searching for. Those people have expressed =
intent, and Google rakes in cash from advertisers intent on capturing it. B=
ecause Google captures the most search attention =E2=80=93 93% of searches =
worldwide go through Google =E2=80=93 it attracts the most advertising doll=
ars of any business on earth. Both demand and supply cost it practically no=
thing to acquire, and ads cost it practically nothing to serve.=C2=A0
In 2022, Facebook/Meta did $116.6 billion in revenue and Google/Alphabet di=
d $282.8 billion in revenue, the vast majority of which, in both cases, cam=
e from serving ads. It=E2=80=99s hard to think of better internet business =
models. But I think OpenAI just did by accident.=C2=A0
Attention with Intelligence
OpenAI=E2=80=99s potential business model is hard to comp directly because =
it=E2=80=99s so many things at once: an aggregator, an API, and a platform.=
=C2=A0
Imagine that a bunch of apps used Google Search as their core feature, Goog=
le was the main place to find those apps, and those apps worked better when=
 you used them in concert with each other through Google, and you=E2=80=99r=
e getting close to what OpenAI might be able to do.=C2=A0
OpenAI hits its partners from all angles:=C2=A0
Attention Grabber. ChatGPT is the front-end for OpenAI, the =E2=80=9Caggreg=
ator=E2=80=9D to which over 100 million users flocked within the first two =
months. ChatGPT will let OpenAI control demand for abundant resources, whic=
h are themselves tailored to OpenAI.=C2=A0
Intelligence API. A number of new products are being built around OpenAI=E2=
=80=99s API and a bunch of incumbent products are re-architecting themselve=
s around OpenAI=E2=80=99s API. Unlike most APIs, which serve non-core funct=
ions, the OpenAI Intelligence API is core to many of these product experien=
ces.=C2=A0
Plugin Play. Products, whether built on OpenAI=E2=80=99s APIs or not, can n=
ow be plugged into ChatGPT itself (and potentially into OpenAI=E2=80=99s In=
telligence API over time), turning the product into both platform and aggre=
gator, and bringing more attention to ChatGPT. Unlike an App Store, which j=
ust lists apps but doesn=E2=80=99t ingest its capabilities, this essentiall=
y turns any plugin into an API that gives ChatGPT its company=E2=80=99s ful=
l capabilities.
By attracting so much user attention with a genuinely excellent product, Op=
enAI has also attracted developers to build with its Intelligence API and o=
n its plugin platform. In the short-term, this is great for developers =E2=
=80=93 they get more capabilities and more users =E2=80=93 but it=E2=80=99s=
 a sort of Faustian bargain. Developers building on the Intelligence API ar=
e relying on OpenAI for their core functionality, and plugin developers are=
 handing their core functionality to OpenAI. In both cases, OpenAI gains mo=
re attention, reach, and power.=C2=A0
But the bullets above are based on what=E2=80=99s been announced to date. I=
=E2=80=99ll save speculation for later. For now, let=E2=80=99s go a little =
deeper into each leg of the stool.=C2=A0
Attention Grabber
Attention is all you need. And ChatGPT is an attention grabber.=C2=A0
Just two months after its launch, it reached 100 million users, the fastest=
 ever to reach that mark by an order of magnitude. While OpenAI hasn=E2=80=
=99t updated that number, and doesn=E2=80=99t release daily active user num=
bers, it=E2=80=99s not hard to imagine that in a year, hundreds of millions=
 of people will start their internetting with ChatGPT each and every day.=
=C2=A0
=C2=A0In Defining Aggregators, Thompson wrote, =E2=80=9CThe key characteris=
tic of Aggregators is that they own the user relationship.=E2=80=9D If peop=
le go to your site to find anything on the internet, you can tell them wher=
e to go. If people open your app to ride, you can tell them whose car to ge=
t in. Owning the customer relationship lets aggregators commoditize their s=
uppliers and capture more value from each transaction.=C2=A0
ChatGPT (and GPT more broadly) takes this a step further and completely dis=
intermediates its =E2=80=9Csuppliers.=E2=80=9D Google can show you any webs=
ite its algorithm wants, and it can summarize the website in a prominent bo=
x up top, but its job is still to send people to websites. ChatGPT, on the =
other hand, reads most of the available content on the internet and spits o=
ut complete answers to any prompt right in the chat. It=E2=80=99s not just =
a starting point, but a destination for an increasing percentage of the thi=
ngs a user might want to do online.=C2=A0=C2=A0
When ChatGPT came out, there was a fair amount of harrumphing from AI gray =
hairs that it wasn=E2=80=99t really a technical advance, just a shiny inter=
face on an old model. That missed the point on the product side =E2=80=93 i=
nterfaces are crucial [ https://substack.com/redirect/be038289-db69-42be-ba=
a7-2128230bc966?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ] =E2=80=93 but it especially missed the point on the business mode=
l side. ChatGPT=E2=80=99s interface was an attention grabber, and once you =
have attention, you can direct it in any way you choose.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Intelligence API
ChatGPT didn=E2=80=99t just capture consumer attention, it captured develop=
ers=E2=80=99 imaginations.=C2=A0
While GPT-3 was already available via API, and while some developers were a=
lready building with it, the buzz around ChatGPT pushed seemingly every dev=
eloper to think about how to incorporate GPT into their products. Something=
 like half of the current YC batch [ https://substack.com/redirect/82d8fb09=
-d71a-4a49-8047-239974f14210?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXX=
epKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is building on OpenAI=E2=80=99s APIs.=C2=A0
These companies are derisively called =E2=80=9CGPT wrappers,=E2=80=9D and m=
any have wondered about their viability as venture-scale businesses. What w=
orries me about these businesses is how much they=E2=80=99re handing over t=
o an API.=C2=A0
In APIs All the Way Down [ https://substack.com/redirect/654b683a-edcb-4125=
-9a02-6c43ca457e3c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ], I pointed out that there seems to be a sweet spot for API-fir=
st companies:
Strong API-first businesses sit in this sweet spot: they provide mission cr=
itical but non-core functionality to their customers, like accepting paymen=
ts, providing cloud security, or sending communications to customers.=C2=A0
Plugging in an API makes a ton of sense when APIs deliver cloud hosting or =
payments or text messages or any number of things that every company needs =
to do but that don=E2=80=99t provide a competitive advantage.=C2=A0
But what happens when APIs deliver intelligence?=C2=A0
OpenAI=E2=80=99s APIs are essentially Intelligence APIs. Write a few lines =
of code, and your product can do a bunch of things that a pretty smart huma=
n could, like answer customer service chats or discover drug formulations o=
r tutor a student. Of course, most of the products that use OpenAI=E2=80=99=
s APIs do other things besides just delivering ChatGPT in a different inter=
face, and they certainly involve some fine-tuning to better address the cus=
tomer=E2=80=99s specific needs, but for most of these products, it really f=
eels like they=E2=80=99re breaking the Cardinal Rule of APIs: don=E2=80=99t=
 outsource the thing that makes your beer taste better [ https://substack.c=
om/redirect/0d75633c-e3bb-4c94-8330-004de0638781?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=C2=A0
But what=E2=80=99s a company to do? Spend hundreds of millions to train the=
ir own models in the hopes of producing something different enough to matte=
r? Not make their products intelligent? This is the Chinese Finger Trap tha=
t=E2=80=99s captured so many companies before. As I wrote in Shopify and th=
e Hard Thing About Easy Things [ https://substack.com/redirect/a48a0ba1-788=
7-461f-ac0c-dc50cedac791?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]:=C2=A0
Here=E2=80=99s the hard thing about easy things: if everyone can do somethi=
ng, there=E2=80=99s no advantage to doing it, but you still have to do it a=
nyway just to keep up.
In just a couple of months, we=E2=80=99re already at a point at which there=
=E2=80=99s no real competitive advantage to using OpenAI=E2=80=99s Intellig=
ence APIs, but there=E2=80=99s a disadvantage for not using them.
From OpenAI=E2=80=99s perspective, however, this is an incredible situation=
=2E Developers have to pay to use OpenAI=E2=
=80=99s APIs, and each company tha=
t writes those few lines of code to incorporate intelligence into their pro=
ducts makes it even more table stakes for the next one. Plus, it gives Open=
AI more attention: now, there are armies of marketers pushing the value of =
OpenAI=E2=80=99s products on its behalf.=C2=A0
Until a week ago, the situation was tenable for GPT wrappers. Some people w=
ould be happy to just use ChatGPT and get an ~80% experience on that specif=
ic thing =E2=80=93 get a good recommendation for a travel itinerary but go =
execute it themselves =E2=80=93 while others would be happy to pay $10/mont=
h for an app that gave more tailored recommendations and booked the trip.=
=C2=A0=C2=A0
Then OpenAI announced ChatGPT plugins [ https://substack.com/redirect/8a25d=
f10-e567-4922-a26f-84ee80c16d1e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjm=
lXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=C2=A0
To read about ChatGPT plugins, how OpenAI could create the Apex Aggregator,=
 and the choices it=E2=80=99s going to have to make=E2=80=A6
Thanks to Dan [ https://substack.com/redirect/eaaee3ce-fc0a-4f86-bedc-a8be1=
98ed21e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
] for editing, Anton [ https://substack.com/redirect/d654c98d-2149-4b75-950=
d-687932066400?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8E=
xkRNpU ] for teaching me about Attention is All You Need, and Ben Thompson =
[ https://substack.com/redirect/eabb6db7-5ddf-426d-a77a-db6ec79983f9?j=3Dey=
J1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] for the insi=
ghts that keep on giving (and congrats on 10 years!)!
That=E2=80=99s all for today. If you found today=E2=80=99s post useful, sha=
re it with a friend or two. If you didn=E2=80=99t, thanks for making it all=
 the way down here anyway :) We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Friday =
with another Weekly Dose of Optimism.
Thanks for reading,=20
Packy

